<seg id=1> Ding Hao Became The First Handicapped University Student Who Grew Up in Chinese Orphanage </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Xinhua News Agency, Hangzhou, September 1 (by Journalist Zhu Guoxian, probationer Guan Zhehui) - Ding Hao, a handicapped student, being an orphan from his childhood and grew up in Hangzhou Children Welfare Institute, received an enrollment notice a few days ago from Hangzhou University and became a student of philosophy and social science major of this university. </seg>
<seg id=3> It is known that Ding Hao, 19 years old in this year, is the first handicapped university student in new China who was adopted by and grew up in Welfare Institute. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> "Upon receipt of the notice, I really want to jump with joy", Ding Hao said, but he is not able to express his excitement by "jumping". </seg>
<seg id=5> A very bad high fever when he was only three made him suffered from the severe sequelae of poliomyelitis. In this year, he was adopted by the Welfare Institute. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> Ding Hao finished his primary school in Welfare Institute and then entered a nearby junior high school in the village. </seg>
<seg id=7> At the beginning, he was under the escort of the teachers of Welfare Institute to and from the school. After grade two he lived at school and was back to Welfare Institute on every Saturday, he was never absent in class regardless of the whether. </seg>
<seg id=8> This year, he attended the university entrance exam and was enrolled by Hangzhou University with eligible marks. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=9> Ding Hao's success is the concentration of efforts from all circles of society. </seg>
<seg id=10> The Children Welfare Institute has loved and taken care of him constantly for sixteen years. Only in last year, the Institute spent more than 3,000 yuan for his tuition fee, study materials, and nourishment. </seg>
<seg id=11> Different circles of the society also give him their hands. </seg>
<seg id=12> Knowing his enrollment in university, Hangzhou Longchang Foodstuff and Oil Trading Company donated 20,000 yuan to assist his study; while the Artificial Limb Factory and other companies gave him the wheel chair, and stick etc. </seg>
</p>
